description:
## Problem

Every fdb command has a top-level `catch (e)` block that formats any exception as `ERROR: $e` and returns 1. This swallows `AppDiedException` and emits `ERROR: AppDiedException(reason: jetsam)` instead of the structured `ERROR: APP_DIED REASON=jetsam` output.

Example in `lib/commands/tap.dart`:
```dart
} catch (e) {
  stderr.writeln('ERROR: $e');  // swallows AppDiedException
  return 1;
}
```

The `AppDiedException` handler in `bin/fdb.dart`'s `main()` is unreachable because the exception is caught by the command first.

## Impact

All commands that catch exceptions (tap, tree, describe, scroll-to, wait, double-tap, longpress, input, back, reload, restart, etc.) will print the wrong output when the app dies.

## Fix

Each command's catch block must re-throw `AppDiedException`:
```dart
} on AppDiedException {
  rethrow;
} catch (e) {
  stderr.writeln('ERROR: $e');
  return 1;
}
```

Affected files: all files in `lib/commands/` that have a top-level `catch (e)` block.

## Related

- fdb-1777300692624 (APP_DIED detection feature — parent)
- fdb-5pa (checkFdbHelper swallowed AppDiedException — fixed)

## Problem

`checkFdbHelper()` in `lib/vm_service.dart` catches ALL exceptions including `AppDiedException`:

```dart
Future<String?> checkFdbHelper() async {
  try {
    final isolateId = await findFlutterIsolateId();
    if (isolateId == null) return null;
    await vmServiceCall(...);
    return isolateId;
  } catch (_) {  // ← swallows AppDiedException!
    return null;
  }
}
```

And commands like `tap`, `tree`, `describe` call `checkFdbHelper()` first. When the app is dead, `vmServiceCall` inside `checkFdbHelper` throws `AppDiedException`, but it gets swallowed and `checkFdbHelper` returns `null`. The command then prints:
```
ERROR: fdb_helper not detected in running app. ...
```
instead of:
```
ERROR: APP_DIED ...
```

## Impact

- Commands that use `checkFdbHelper()` (tap, tree, describe, double-tap, longpress, scroll-to, etc.) never emit `APP_DIED`
- The user/agent sees a misleading fdb_helper error instead of the real root cause

## Fix

`checkFdbHelper` should re-throw `AppDiedException` specifically:
```dart
} on AppDiedException {
  rethrow;
} catch (_) {
  return null;
}
```

Similarly, `findFlutterIsolateId` catches all errors too — review the full call chain.

## Related

- fdb-1777300692624 (APP_DIED detection feature — parent)
- fdb-92d (APP_DIED not emitted on macOS when flutter-tools PID is still alive)
